<br>
Epic pet quads for 67, has 3k hp, and has 75% (or so) haste.<br>
<br>
Charmed pet quads for 150, has 8k hp, and has 66% haste (and yeah, the enchanter needs to bring some weapons with him).<br>
<br>
In groups, the DS is irrelevant.  Enchanter pet crushes ours.<br>
<br>
Soloing, the DS is more than compensated for by increased damage and hp.  Also the enchanter pet has a lesser DS and is fighting a slowed mob.  Not to mention that an enchanter, with C2 or Kodiak's, can outdamage us in any situation where magic-based nukes land and can handle adds with ease.<br>
<br>
Add enchanters to the list of classes that outsolo a mage at the highest level of play, along with wizard, shaman, monk, shadow knight, paladin, ranger, druid, and necro.<br>
<br>
At least we outsolo clerics.<br>
<br>
Utuno, Arch Mage <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=rhasinfirestorm>Rhasin Firestorm</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 177<br> <font color=#333333>(1/14/02 11:14:37 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm30.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=55.topic&index=36>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Dire charm</span><hr size=1> I posted this letter over to the Developers Corner. I don't know if it'd do any good posting it here, too, but hey.. information of what's stated can't always be bad, can it?<br>
<br>
Anyways, here goes:<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Greetings,<br>
<br>
  I'm going to be brief, and hopefully proactively send in a comment concerning Dire Charm.<br>
<br>
  First off, I kind of applaud the thinking that went into this. Sort of. I mean, it could become a new class defining trait of Enchanters, since one of their roles is messing with the minds of others.<br>
<br>
  However, I recall what happened when Enchanters used Charm to take down the Avatar of War in Kael. Rather than influence only the abused skill (Charm) by making the giants more resistant to it (well, for a time they were), it was deemed that a change in the way mobs aggro should be in order. Now, most enchanters only use charm to turn a bad situation into a good one (rather than mez and fight, let the mob help you out). That's cool. <br>
<br>
  What all this mob aggro change did, though, is drastically affect how pets are viewed by NPC's. Before, if the pet was outdamaging, the pet took damage. Now.. the pet's got to do some serious serious damage in order to get 1 or 2 hits. While this is sort of good (free damage) it means that the pet cannot, nor will ever, be able to outtaunt a PC within range, even if that PC only did 1 point of damage to the mob and the pet did 10,000. This makes magician pets in particular, relegeated to pure damage dealing creatures in a group, not a potential tank. Perhaps this is good? Perhaps not. Any PC should be able to outtaunt a pet, but if not, the pet really should take a little more abuse than it does now.<br>
<br>
  At any rate, my concern is now with the Dire Charm skill. As it is right now, so long as this skill goes off right, and the enchanter latches onto the creature, you've just gone in and made Kael possible all over again. Perminent charm, why worry about this thing turning on you, right? Aego, Speed, many giants, no tanks, and several clerics. Well, I can envision the Avatar of War going down fairly easily against 5-10 of his local brethren that hit in excess of 130+ per hit, sped up, duelwielding.. anything (get a mage to summon a pair of daggers, since weapon damage does not affect pets nor NPC's), buffed to the hilt, and doing better damage (and absorbing more damage) than any player could.<br>
<br>
  I see this as a potential problem, and /if/ someone does it, so will you, I'm sure. What I want to TRY to get you at Verant to understand is that if you suddenly deem that Dire Charm is overpowered, like many Magicians fear it might be, than PLEASE DO NOT wield a big axe and alter ALL pets again. The change was drastic and horrific for us the first time. Sad to say, we're expecting to feel the brunt of this (what we feel) impending nerf.<br>
<br>
  I can suggest a few things that would strip Dire Charm of some of it's overpoweringness, yet still let it be what it's supposed to be.<br>
<br>
1) Forbid casting any beneficial spells on any creature that is charmed.<br>
<br>
2) Forbid charmed spell casters (ie: cleric mobs) from using their spells on themselves or others.<br>
<br>
3) Perhaps slow health regen on charmed mobs, so if used too much, the creature has a life expectancy. (though with the former two fixes, this one might not be required).<br>
<br>
  Also, a suggestion or two to help out pets be able to take a blow or two again. This might also fix other issues, concerning pets and poor performance at upper levels:<br>
<br>
1) Use the casters level instead of the pet's level for determining how 'vulnerable' the creature in range is.<br>
<br>
2) Remove the block that pets cannot take agression once a proper fix for pet vulnerability is in place. (there seems to be a forcable block, since things like the Fungus Shrooms in FG will cry out their defiance of my pet00, yet never once turn to hit him. That cry being a common 'I'm switching targets' clue)<br>
<br>
3) Improve the pet levels a bit (though not necessarily the damage caps) to lessen their vulnerability. This improvement in pet levels would seem to affect only landing spells, to-hit and damage-taken calculations, though might also include aggro radius reductions.<br>
<br>
  I appreciate any time you take in listening to me and my worries. Any information in here, I do ask that you keep in mind, should the situation with Dire Charm come to a problem. Magicians that rely on their pets already suffer from one bad solution on their main source of damage absorbtion. Two equally bad solutions could very likely render the magician pet a useless comodity.<br>
<br>
Rhasin Firestorm<br>
Magician of the 55th Season<br>
Prexus<br>
<br>
